        <h2>History & Mission</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="gardens__body">
          <p>The Anderton Therapeutic Gardens Society (ATGS) has one simple mission statement: </p>

              <p class="quote">“We are a volunteer society that provides a unique therapeutic garden through diverse,
                   enjoyable, interactive and healing activities for people of all ages and abilities.”</p>


          <p>The concept of creating the therapeutic gardens came about in 1996 when founders Joy and Bill
               Georgeson got a little encouragement from Christine Pollard, Horticultural 
               Therapist at Providence Farms in Duncan. A 30 year lease for a two acre parcel 
               of land from the owners of the Anderton Nursery, Ellen Presley and Karl Opelka, 
               was secured in 1997 (a gift for just $1 per year) and the ATGS was officially registered.</p>

               <p>Ground was broken in the Spring of 1998 and the staff consisted of just
                    10 people at the time. The society was spearheaded by Joy & Bill for a number of years, 
                    drawing in a lot of others to help. They did all the fundraising, labour, public relations, 
                    and so much more. The number of volunteers swelled to approximately 40 members for much of that 
                    time. Bill passed away in 2014 and Joy continues to be actively involved in the Gardens.
            </p>


      </div>
